<p></p>.<p><a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/blood_in_urine/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Blood in the urine</a> may or may 
not be accompanied by <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/pain_management/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">pain</a>, but it is always abnormal and should be 
further investigated by a health care professional. Painful blood in the urine can be caused by a number of 
disorders, including stones and infections in the urinary tract. 
Painless blood in the urine can also be due to many causes, including <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/cancer/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">cancer</a>. 
Blood in the urine is also referred to as <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/blood_in_urine/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">hematuria</a>. Visible blood in the urine is referred to as <i>gross hematuria</i>, while blood in the urine that is not visible to the naked eye is referred to as <i>microscopic hematuria</i>.</p>.<p class="credits">REFERENCE:<br><br>Kasper, D.L., et al., eds. <i>Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine, 19th Ed</i>. United States: McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.</p>